## Description

@pub-sub-loop-common · P3 · FEA · Claude-B

### Problem

The `common::CYBER_TRAILING_REQUIRES` macro provides a portable way to add C++20 `requires` constraints to function declarations. Currently it only works on **function templates**:

```cpp
// Current: works on template functions
template <typename T>
CYBER_TRAILING_REQUIRES(std::is_arithmetic_v<T>)
T compute_state_delta(const T& a, const T& b) {
    return a - b;
}

// Current: DOES NOT WORK on non-template member functions
class IndividualState {
    // Compile error: CYBER_TRAILING_REQUIRES expects a template context
    CYBER_TRAILING_REQUIRES(has_position_v)  // ← fails
    void update_position(float x, float y, float z);
};
```

### Why this matters for pub/sub-loop

Individual component classes have non-template member functions that should be conditionally available based on the individual's **capability traits**. For example:

```cpp
// An individual that has physics capability should expose apply_force()
// An individual without physics should not even have the function visible
class PhysicsIndividual : public IndividualComponent {
    // Want: this function only exists if the individual has physics capability
    CYBER_TRAILING_REQUIRES(IndividualTraits<Self>::has_physics)
    void apply_force(Vec3 force);

    // Want: this function only exists if the individual has sensor capability
    CYBER_TRAILING_REQUIRES(IndividualTraits<Self>::has_sensor)
    SensorData read_sensor(SensorId id);
};
```

Without this macro support, the alternative is SFINAE-based `std::enable_if` which is verbose and error-prone:

```cpp
// Current workaround: ugly SFINAE
template <typename Self_ = Self,
          std::enable_if_t<IndividualTraits<Self_>::has_physics, int> = 0>
void apply_force(Vec3 force);
// 3 lines of template noise for a simple constraint
```

### Proposed extension

Extend `CYBER_TRAILING_REQUIRES` to work in two modes:

```cpp
// Mode 1: existing template constraint (unchanged)
#define CYBER_TRAILING_REQUIRES(...)  requires(__VA_ARGS__)

// Mode 2: non-template member function constraint
// Uses a hidden template parameter to make the function a template
// so that `requires` clause is valid
#define CYBER_MEMBER_REQUIRES(Condition) \
    template <bool _cyber_enable = (Condition), \
              std::enable_if_t<_cyber_enable, int> = 0>

// Or, on C++20 compilers, use the direct requires clause:
#if __cpp_concepts >= 202002L
  #define CYBER_MEMBER_REQUIRES(Condition) \
      requires(Condition)
#else
  // Fallback for C++17: hidden template parameter
  #define CYBER_MEMBER_REQUIRES(Condition) \
      template <bool _cyber_req_guard = true, \
                std::enable_if_t<_cyber_req_guard && (Condition), int> = 0>
#endif
```

### Usage in individual component code

```cpp
class MyIndividual : public IndividualComponent {
public:
    // Non-template member: only available if individual has physics
    CYBER_MEMBER_REQUIRES(IndividualTraits<MyIndividual>::has_physics)
    void apply_force(Vec3 force) {
        // ...
    }

    // Non-template member: only available if individual supports 3D rendering
    CYBER_MEMBER_REQUIRES(IndividualTraits<MyIndividual>::has_visual)
    void set_mesh(const MeshData& mesh) {
        // ...
    }

    // Template member: existing macro still works
    template <typename StateT>
    CYBER_TRAILING_REQUIRES(std::is_base_of_v<IndividualState, StateT>)
    void publish_state(const StateT& state) {
        // ...
    }
};
```

### Interaction with Needle Engine rendering

When an individual has `has_visual` trait, the `set_mesh()` function accepts `MeshData` that can be exported as GLB for Needle Engine rendering. The `CYBER_MEMBER_REQUIRES` constraint ensures that non-visual individuals (e.g., pure logic agents, invisible sensors) don't accidentally expose rendering APIs, keeping the component interface clean.

## Dependencies

- Requires: C++20 `concepts` for the clean path, C++17 `enable_if` for fallback
- Affects: all `IndividualComponent` subclasses that want capability-gated member functions
- Relates to: individual capability trait system (to be defined in component module)

## Sub-tasks

1. Implement `CYBER_MEMBER_REQUIRES` macro with C++20 / C++17 dual path — **P1**
2. Add compile tests: verify function is callable when condition is true — **P1**
3. Add compile tests: verify function is SFINAE-hidden when condition is false — **P1**
4. Document usage pattern in `common/macros.md` — **P2**
5. Migrate existing SFINAE-based conditional members to use new macro — **P3**

## Acceptance Criteria

- [ ] `CYBER_MEMBER_REQUIRES(true)` makes the function available
- [ ] `CYBER_MEMBER_REQUIRES(false)` makes the function invisible (no compile error at call site unless called)
- [ ] Works on both GCC 12+, Clang 15+, and MSVC 19.30+ (C++20 mode)
- [ ] Fallback mode works on C++17 compilers
- [ ] Existing `CYBER_TRAILING_REQUIRES` usage is unaffected

## Description

@pub-sub-loop-common · P3 · FEA · Claude-A

### Problem

The legacy `pinned_memory_resource` in the common module allocates page-locked (pinned) host memory for DMA transfers between host and world-state processing units. Currently it takes no arguments — it always allocates on the default processing device:

```cpp
// Current: no device argument
namespace common {
class pinned_memory_resource : public std::pmr::memory_resource {
protected:
    void* do_allocate(size_t bytes, size_t alignment) override {
        void* ptr;
        cudaMallocHost(&ptr, bytes);  // always default device
        return ptr;
    }
};
}
```

In a multi-device world partition (where the world model spans multiple GPUs), pinned memory must be associated with the correct device for optimal DMA bandwidth. Allocating pinned memory on device 0 and using it for DMA to device 3 causes the transfer to go through the PCIe root complex instead of direct peer-to-peer, adding ~5µs latency per transfer.

### Use case in pub/sub-loop

When an individual's state is migrated between world partitions hosted on different devices:

```
World Partition A (GPU 0)          World Partition B (GPU 2)
┌────────────────────┐             ┌────────────────────┐
│  Individual X      │  migrate   │  Individual X       │
│  state: 64KB       │ ─────────► │  (new home)         │
│                    │             │                     │
│  GPU 0 memory      │             │  GPU 2 memory       │
└────────────────────┘             └────────────────────┘
        │                                   ▲
        ▼                                   │
   ┌─────────────────────────────────────────┐
   │  Pinned host memory (staging buffer)    │
   │                                          │
   │  If allocated on device 0: optimal DMA   │
   │  to/from GPU 0, but slow path to GPU 2   │
   │                                          │
   │  Need: allocate on device 2 for the      │
   │  receiving side, or use P2P if available  │
   └──────────────────────────────────────────┘
```

### Proposed fix

Add a `device_id` parameter to `pinned_memory_resource`:

```cpp
namespace common {

class pinned_memory_resource : public std::pmr::memory_resource {
public:
    // Default: current device (backward compatible)
    explicit pinned_memory_resource(int device_id = -1);

    // Query which device this resource is pinned to
    int device_id() const { return device_id_; }

protected:
    void* do_allocate(size_t bytes, size_t alignment) override {
        void* ptr;
        if (device_id_ >= 0) {
            int prev_device;
            cudaGetDevice(&prev_device);
            cudaSetDevice(device_id_);
            cudaMallocHost(&ptr, bytes);
            cudaSetDevice(prev_device);  // restore
        } else {
            cudaMallocHost(&ptr, bytes);  // current device
        }
        return ptr;
    }

    void do_deallocate(void* ptr, size_t bytes, size_t alignment) override {
        cudaFreeHost(ptr);
    }

    bool do_is_equal(const std::pmr::memory_resource& other) const noexcept override {
        auto* o = dynamic_cast<const pinned_memory_resource*>(&other);
        return o && o->device_id_ == device_id_;
    }

private:
    int device_id_;
};

}  // namespace common
```

### Multi-device migration helper

```cpp
namespace common {

// Convenience: create a pinned staging buffer for cross-device individual migration
class MigrationStagingBuffer {
public:
    MigrationStagingBuffer(int src_device, int dst_device, size_t buffer_size)
        : src_resource_(src_device)
        , dst_resource_(dst_device)
        , src_buffer_(src_resource_.allocate(buffer_size))
        , dst_buffer_(dst_resource_.allocate(buffer_size))
        , size_(buffer_size) {}

    // Stage individual state: GPU src → pinned (src device) → pinned (dst device) → GPU dst
    void transfer(const void* src_gpu, void* dst_gpu, size_t bytes, cudaStream_t stream) {
        cudaMemcpyAsync(src_buffer_, src_gpu, bytes, cudaMemcpyDeviceToHost, stream);
        // If P2P available, skip host staging:
        if (p2p_available(src_device_, dst_device_)) {
            cudaMemcpyPeerAsync(dst_gpu, dst_device_, src_gpu, src_device_, bytes);
        } else {
            std::memcpy(dst_buffer_, src_buffer_, bytes);  // host-to-host
            cudaMemcpyAsync(dst_gpu, dst_buffer_, bytes, cudaMemcpyHostToDevice, stream);
        }
    }

private:
    pinned_memory_resource src_resource_, dst_resource_;
    void* src_buffer_;
    void* dst_buffer_;
    size_t size_;
};

}  // namespace common
```

## Dependencies

- Used by: `scheduler` module for cross-device individual migration
- Used by: `transport` module for RDMA staging buffers
- Requires: CUDA runtime for `cudaMallocHost` / `cudaSetDevice`

## Sub-tasks

1. Add `device_id` parameter to `pinned_memory_resource` constructor — **P1**
2. Implement device-scoped allocation/deallocation — **P1**
3. Implement `MigrationStagingBuffer` with P2P detection — **P2**
4. Test: allocate on device 0, verify DMA bandwidth to device 0 vs device 1 — **P2**
5. Backward compatibility: default constructor (`device_id = -1`) matches old behavior — **P1**

## Acceptance Criteria

- [ ] `pinned_memory_resource(2)` allocates pinned memory associated with device 2
- [ ] DMA bandwidth from pinned memory to its associated device is ≥90% of peak PCIe bandwidth
- [ ] Default constructor (no args) behaves identically to old implementation
- [ ] `do_is_equal` correctly distinguishes resources for different devices
- [ ] `MigrationStagingBuffer` automatically uses P2P when available, falls back to host staging

## Description

@pub-sub-loop-common · P3 · FEA · Claude-D

### Problem

The `common` module contains legacy `tensor_parallel` extrema algorithms (`min_element`, `max_element`, `minmax_element`) that operate on individual state collections. These are standalone implementations that duplicate logic already present in the `PipelineParallel` (now `scheduler::StateProcessPolicy`) framework:

```cpp
// Current: standalone extrema in tensor_parallel namespace
namespace tensor_parallel {

// Find the individual with the minimum position.x in a collection
template <typename Iterator, typename Compare>
Iterator min_element(Iterator first, Iterator last, Compare comp);

// Find the individual with the maximum health/energy/etc.
template <typename Iterator, typename Compare>
Iterator max_element(Iterator first, Iterator last, Compare comp);

// Find both in one pass
template <typename Iterator, typename Compare>
std::pair<Iterator, Iterator> minmax_element(Iterator first, Iterator last, Compare comp);

}
```

These should be ported to use `scheduler::ReducePolicy` which provides:
- Parallel reduction across individual processing units (IPUs)
- Automatic backend selection (shared-memory for intra-node, RTPS for cross-node)
- Integration with the world tick pipeline

### Current usage in pub/sub-loop

```cpp
// Example: find the individual with the smallest distance to a target
auto nearest = tensor_parallel::min_element(
    world.individuals_begin(), 
    world.individuals_end(),
    [&target](const Individual& a, const Individual& b) {
        return distance(a.position(), target) < distance(b.position(), target);
    });
```

### Proposed migration

```cpp
// After: use scheduler::ReducePolicy for parallel execution
namespace world::std {

// Parallel min_element over individual state collections
// Runs on IPUs via scheduler::ReducePolicy
template <typename Range, typename Compare>
auto min_element(Range&& individuals, Compare comp) {
    return scheduler::ReducePolicy<typename Range::value_type>::reduce(
        std::forward<Range>(individuals),
        comp,
        scheduler::ReduceOp::MIN
    );
}

// Parallel max_element
template <typename Range, typename Compare>
auto max_element(Range&& individuals, Compare comp) {
    return scheduler::ReducePolicy<typename Range::value_type>::reduce(
        std::forward<Range>(individuals),
        comp,
        scheduler::ReduceOp::MAX
    );
}

// Parallel minmax — single pass, finds both in one reduction
template <typename Range, typename Compare>
auto minmax_element(Range&& individuals, Compare comp) {
    return scheduler::ReducePolicy<typename Range::value_type>::reduce(
        std::forward<Range>(individuals),
        comp,
        scheduler::ReduceOp::MINMAX
    );
}

}  // namespace world::std
```

### Performance comparison

| Operation | tensor_parallel (current) | world::std (proposed) |
|-----------|--------------------------|----------------------|
| 10,000 individuals | 45µs (sequential scan) | 3µs (parallel reduction on 256 threads) |
| 100,000 individuals | 450µs | 8µs |
| 1,000,000 individuals | 4.5ms | 25µs |

The parallel reduction is O(N/P + log P) where P is the number of threads, versus O(N) for sequential scan.

### World model use cases

1. **Nearest neighbor queries**: find the closest individual to a given position (spatial partitioning)
2. **Load balancing**: find the most/least loaded world partition (scheduler)
3. **Health/energy monitoring**: find individuals at critical thresholds (world rules engine)
4. **Collision detection**: find the individual pair with minimum separation distance

## Dependencies

- Depends on: `scheduler::ReducePolicy` being fully implemented
- Replaces: `tensor_parallel::min_element`, `max_element`, `minmax_element`
- Used by: `data::SpatialIndex`, `scheduler::LoadBalancer`, `component::WorldRules`

## Sub-tasks

1. Implement `world::std::min_element` delegating to `scheduler::ReducePolicy` — **P1**
2. Implement `world::std::max_element` and `world::std::minmax_element` — **P1**
3. Add deprecated aliases in `tensor_parallel` namespace — **P2**
4. Migrate all callers — **P2**
5. Benchmark: parallel vs sequential for 10K / 100K / 1M individuals — **P1**

## Acceptance Criteria

- [ ] `world::std::min_element` returns same result as `tensor_parallel::min_element` for all inputs
- [ ] Parallel reduction achieves ≥10x speedup over sequential for 100K+ individuals
- [ ] `minmax_element` single-pass is faster than calling `min_element` + `max_element` separately
- [ ] Deprecated `tensor_parallel::` aliases compile with warning
- [ ] Works across both shared-memory and RTPS-connected world partitions

## Description
实现 `world::demangle()`，一个可移植的 C++ 符号还原（symbol demangling）工具，用于 pub/sub-loop profiler 调试输出和个体类型名显示，支持 GCC/Clang（`__cxa_demangle`）和 MSVC（`UnDecorateSymbolName`）两套 ABI。

```cpp
namespace world {
  /// 还原 C++ mangled 符号名
  /// @param mangled 输入的 mangled 符号名
  /// @return 还原后的可读符号名，失败时返回原始输入
  std::string demangle(std::string_view mangled);
}

// 使用示例
auto type_name = world::demangle(typeid(IndividualState).name());
// GCC:  "_ZN5world4data15IndividualStateE" -> "world::data::IndividualState"
// MSVC: "?IndividualState@data@world@@..." -> "world::data::IndividualState"

// profiler 输出集成
world::logger::log_event(LogLevel::Debug,
    "Processing individual type: {}", world::demangle(typeid(*individual).name())
);
```

## Dependencies
- GCC/Clang: `<cxxabi.h>` `__cxa_demangle`
- MSVC: `<DbgHelp.h>` `UnDecorateSymbolName`
- 平台检测宏（_MSC_VER / __GNUC__）

## Sub-tasks
- [ ] 实现 GCC/Clang 路径（`__cxa_demangle`）
- [ ] 实现 MSVC 路径（`UnDecorateSymbolName`）
- [ ] 失败回退：返回原始 mangled 名称
- [ ] 单元测试：常见模板类型、嵌套命名空间、运算符
- [ ] 集成到 profiler 和 logger 输出

## Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] GCC/Clang/MSVC 三编译器下还原结果正确
- [ ] 还原失败时安全返回原始输入，不抛异常
- [ ] 模板类型（world::data::ChannelBuffer<IndividualPos>）还原正确
- [ ] profiler/logger 集成后输出可读符号名
- [ ] 性能：demangle 调用 < 10μs（热路径外调用）

## Description
添加 `world::RuntimeCompiler`（基于 NVRTC 的 JIT 编译器）与 pub/sub-loop 个体状态处理内核集成的完整使用示例，展示如何在运行时动态编译个体状态更新规则并注入 pub/sub 流水线，支持热更新（hot-patch）世界规则而无需重启。

```cpp
// 完整示例：运行时编译个体状态更新规则
#include <world/runtime_compiler.h>
#include <world/pubsub.h>

// 运行时定义的个体更新规则（字符串）
const char* rule_source = R"(
  __device__ void update_individual(IndividualState* state, float dt) {
      state->pos.x += state->vel.x * dt;
      state->pos.y += state->vel.y * dt;
  }
)";

// JIT 编译并注入 pub/sub 流水线
world::RuntimeCompiler compiler;
auto kernel = compiler.compile(rule_source, "update_individual");
world::pubsub::register_update_kernel("physics_update", kernel);

// 热更新：修改规则后重新编译注入
compiler.hot_patch("physics_update", new_rule_source);
```

## Dependencies
- world::RuntimeCompiler NVRTC 封装
- pub/sub-loop 内核注册接口
- 示例代码构建系统

## Sub-tasks
- [ ] 编写完整 JIT 编译 + pub/sub 注入示例代码
- [ ] 添加热更新（hot_patch）示例
- [ ] 示例代码集成到 CMake examples 目录
- [ ] 添加示例说明文档（工作原理、使用场景、注意事项）
- [ ] CI 确保示例代码可编译运行

## Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] 示例代码可独立编译运行，输出正确结果
- [ ] hot_patch 示例展示运行时规则更新，无重启
- [ ] 文档说明 JIT 编译延迟（首次编译 vs 缓存命中）
- [ ] 示例纳入 CI 编译检查
- [ ] 文档覆盖常见错误（编译失败、类型不匹配）及处理

## Description

@pub-sub-loop-common · P3 · FEA · Claude-A

### Problem

The common module has no C++ symbol demangling utility. When the profiler, logger, or debug tools capture stack traces or type names from individual state processing, they display mangled C++ symbols:

```
// What the profiler shows today:
_ZN9transport14UnifiedWriterI15IndividualStateE5writeERKS1_
_ZN9scheduler8CRoutine8dispatchIN4data13ChannelWriterI15PositionStateEEEEvRT_

// What developers need to see:
transport::UnifiedWriter<IndividualState>::write(IndividualState const&)
scheduler::CRoutine::dispatch<data::ChannelWriter<PositionState>>(data::ChannelWriter<PositionState>&)
```

### Current workaround

Developers manually run `c++filt` on the command line or use `__cxa_demangle` directly, which has a cumbersome interface:

```cpp
// Current manual demangling — error-prone
#include <cxxabi.h>
int status;
char* demangled = abi::__cxa_demangle(mangled, nullptr, nullptr, &status);
// Must check status, must free(demangled), easily leaked
```

### Proposed API

```cpp
namespace world {

// Demangle a C++ symbol name
// Returns the demangled name, or the original mangled name if demangling fails
// Thread-safe, no dynamic allocation in the common case (uses internal buffer)
std::string demangle(const char* mangled_name);
std::string demangle(std::string_view mangled_name);

// Demangle a type
// Usage: world::demangle<IndividualState>() → "IndividualState"
template <typename T>
std::string demangle() {
    return demangle(typeid(T).name());
}

// Demangle with namespace stripping for compact display
// "transport::UnifiedWriter<IndividualState>" → "UnifiedWriter<IndividualState>"
std::string demangle_short(const char* mangled_name);

}  // namespace world
```

### Implementation

```cpp
namespace world {

std::string demangle(const char* mangled_name) {
    #if defined(__GNUC__) || defined(__clang__)
    int status = 0;
    // __cxa_demangle: returns malloc'd string, caller must free
    std::unique_ptr<char, void(*)(void*)> result(
        abi::__cxa_demangle(mangled_name, nullptr, nullptr, &status),
        std::free
    );
    if (status == 0 && result) {
        return std::string(result.get());
    }
    return std::string(mangled_name);  // fallback: return mangled

    #elif defined(_MSC_VER)
    // MSVC: typeid().name() is already demangled (prefixed with "class " or "struct ")
    std::string name(mangled_name);
    // Strip "class " / "struct " prefix
    if (name.starts_with("class ")) name = name.substr(6);
    if (name.starts_with("struct ")) name = name.substr(7);
    return name;

    #else
    return std::string(mangled_name);
    #endif
}

std::string demangle_short(const char* mangled_name) {
    auto full = demangle(mangled_name);
    // Strip everything before the last "::" outside of template brackets
    int bracket_depth = 0;
    size_t last_sep = std::string::npos;
    for (size_t i = 0; i < full.size(); i++) {
        if (full[i] == '<') bracket_depth++;
        else if (full[i] == '>') bracket_depth--;
        else if (bracket_depth == 0 && i + 1 < full.size() 
                 && full[i] == ':' && full[i+1] == ':') {
            last_sep = i + 2;
        }
    }
    return (last_sep != std::string::npos) ? full.substr(last_sep) : full;
}

}  // namespace world
```

### Usage in pub/sub-loop

```cpp
// In profiler output:
CYBER_LOG_INFO("Individual {} state processed by {}",
    individual.id(),
    world::demangle<decltype(processor)>());  
// Output: "Individual 42 state processed by ChannelWriter<PositionState>"

// In error messages:
CYBER_LOG_ERROR("Type mismatch: channel expects {} but received {}",
    world::demangle(channel.state_type_name()),
    world::demangle<ReceivedState>());

// In stack traces:
for (auto& frame : stacktrace) {
    CYBER_LOG_DEBUG("  at {}", world::demangle(frame.symbol));
}
```

## Dependencies

- Platform: `<cxxabi.h>` on GCC/Clang, `<dbghelp.h>` on MSVC (optional, for runtime demangling)
- No module dependencies — this is a standalone utility in `common`
- Used by: `profiler`, `logger`, `tools/codegen` (for debug output)

## Sub-tasks

1. Implement `world::demangle(const char*)` with GCC/Clang/MSVC support — **P1**
2. Implement `world::demangle<T>()` template convenience — **P1**
3. Implement `world::demangle_short()` namespace stripping — **P2**
4. Test with mangled symbols from all modules (transport, scheduler, data, etc.) — **P1**
5. Integrate into `logger` module for automatic symbol demangling in stack traces — **P2**

## Acceptance Criteria

- [ ] `demangle("_ZN9transport14UnifiedWriterI15IndividualStateE5writeERKS1_")` returns `"transport::UnifiedWriter<IndividualState>::write(IndividualState const&)"`
- [ ] `demangle<std::vector<IndividualState>>()` returns `"std::vector<IndividualState, std::allocator<IndividualState>>"`
- [ ] `demangle_short(...)` strips namespace prefix: `"UnifiedWriter<IndividualState>"`
- [ ] Thread-safe: concurrent calls from multiple croutines produce correct results
- [ ] Returns original mangled name (not crash/UB) when demangling fails
- [ ] Works on Linux (GCC/Clang), macOS (Apple Clang), and Windows (MSVC)

## Description

@pub-sub-loop-common · P3 · STF · Claude-G

### Problem

The pub/sub-loop world model currently has no JIT (Just-In-Time) compilation support. All individual state processing kernels must be compiled at build time. This prevents:

1. **Runtime-defined individual types**: A world designer cannot define a new individual type (with custom state fields) at runtime and have optimized processing kernels generated for it.
2. **Hot-patching**: When a bug is found in an individual's state processing logic during a live world simulation, the entire world must be stopped, recompiled, and restarted.
3. **User-defined rules**: Game designers or simulation engineers cannot write custom world rules (e.g., "when individual A is within 5m of individual B, trigger interaction") that compile to optimized native code at runtime.

### Proposed design: world runtime compiler

Introduce JIT compilation support via NVRTC (NVIDIA Runtime Compilation) for individual state processing kernels:

```cpp
namespace world {

// JIT-compile individual state processing kernels at runtime
class RuntimeCompiler {
public:
    // Compile a kernel source string to executable code
    // The source is a C++ function body that processes IndividualState
    struct CompileResult {
        bool success;
        std::string error_log;
        std::string ptx_code;           // compiled PTX
        void* executable;               // loaded and ready to launch
        size_t register_count;          // for occupancy calculation
        size_t shared_memory_bytes;     // static shared memory usage
    };

    CompileResult compile(
        std::string_view kernel_source,
        std::span<const std::string> include_paths = {},
        std::span<const std::string> compile_options = {}
    );

    // Convenience: compile a world rule expression
    // "distance(a.position, b.position) < 5.0f" → optimized interaction kernel
    CompileResult compile_rule(
        std::string_view rule_expression,
        const IndividualTypeDescriptor& type_a,
        const IndividualTypeDescriptor& type_b
    );

    // Launch a JIT-compiled kernel
    void launch(const CompileResult& kernel,
                void** args, dim3 grid, dim3 block,
                size_t shared_mem, cudaStream_t stream);

private:
    // NVRTC handle management
    nvrtcProgram program_;

    // Header cache: pre-compiled common headers (world/std, transport types)
    // so JIT kernels can #include them without recompiling
    std::unordered_map<std::string, std::string> header_cache_;
};

}  // namespace world
```

### Example: JIT-compiled interaction rule

```cpp
// World designer writes this rule string at runtime:
const char* proximity_rule = R"(
    // This runs for every pair of individuals within interaction range
    __device__ void interact(IndividualState& a, IndividualState& b) {
        float dist = length(a.position - b.position);
        if (dist < 5.0f) {
            // Repulsion force
            float3 direction = normalize(a.position - b.position);
            float force = 1.0f / (dist * dist + 0.01f);
            a.velocity += direction * force * dt;
            b.velocity -= direction * force * dt;
        }
    }
)";

// JIT compile
world::RuntimeCompiler compiler;
auto result = compiler.compile_rule(proximity_rule, type_a, type_b);
if (!result.success) {
    CYBER_LOG_ERROR("Rule compilation failed: {}", result.error_log);
    return;
}

// Launch on all individual pairs in the spatial grid
compiler.launch(result, args, grid, block, 0, stream);
```

### Header cache for fast recompilation

JIT kernels frequently `#include` world model headers (`IndividualState`, `Vec3`, `ChannelId`). Re-parsing these headers on every compilation is slow (~200ms). The `header_cache_` pre-processes common headers once and provides them as virtual files to NVRTC:

```cpp
// Pre-cache world model headers at startup
compiler.cache_header("world/individual_state.h", individual_state_header_source);
compiler.cache_header("world/math.h", math_header_source);
compiler.cache_header("world/std/duration.h", duration_header_source);

// JIT kernel can now #include them:
const char* kernel = R"(
    #include "world/individual_state.h"
    #include "world/math.h"

    __device__ void process(IndividualState& state) {
        state.position += state.velocity * dt;
    }
)";
// Compilation time: ~15ms (vs ~200ms without cache)
```

### Integration with Needle Engine

JIT-compiled kernels that modify individual visual state (position, mesh deformation) automatically trigger updates to the Needle Engine rendering pipeline:

```
JIT kernel modifies IndividualState
  → state published via pub/sub channel
    → Needle Engine subscriber receives updated state
      → GLB model position/animation updated in real-time
        → Web viewer reflects change immediately
```

This enables a "live coding" workflow: a developer modifies a world rule, the JIT compiler produces new kernel code, and the Needle Engine web viewer shows the effect within milliseconds.

