## Description

@pub-sub-loop-common · P3 · FEA · Claude-A

### Problem

The low-level `world::parallel` API (the foundation layer for all parallel individual state processing algorithms) currently requires callers to pass iterator pairs:

```cpp
// Current: iterator-based API
namespace world::parallel {
    template <typename InputIt, typename OutputIt, typename Op>
    void transform(InputIt first, InputIt last, OutputIt d_first, Op op);

    template <typename InputIt, typename T, typename BinaryOp>
    T reduce(InputIt first, InputIt last, T init, BinaryOp op);
}
```

This forces callers who already have raw pointers to wrap them in iterators:

```cpp
// Caller has raw pointers from transport::ZeroCopyRegion
IndividualState* states_ptr = zero_copy_region.data();
size_t count = zero_copy_region.size();

// Must construct iterators just to call the API:
world::parallel::transform(states_ptr, states_ptr + count, output_ptr, update_op);
// This works because raw pointers ARE iterators, but...

// The problem is internal: parallel::transform dispatches to a backend
// that extracts the raw pointer BACK from the iterator:
//   auto* ptr = &(*first);  // ← extracts pointer from iterator
// This round-trip (pointer → iterator → pointer) is fragile:
// - Fails for fancy iterators that don't have addressable elements
// - Prevents passing device-specific metadata (NUMA node, memory pool ID)
// - The internal raw_pointer_cast<T>(first) is implementation-defined
```

### Proposed fix

Add overloads that accept pointers + count directly, avoiding the iterator round-trip:

```cpp
namespace world::parallel {

// New: pointer + count overloads
template <typename T, typename Op>
void transform(T* input, size_t count, T* output, Op op);

template <typename T, typename BinaryOp>
T reduce(const T* input, size_t count, T init, BinaryOp op);

template <typename T, typename Pred>
size_t select(const T* input, size_t count, T* output, Pred pred);

template <typename T, typename Compare>
void sort(T* data, size_t count, Compare comp);

// With memory pool context: tells the backend which pool the pointers came from
// so it can optimize locality (e.g., schedule on the IPU nearest to the memory)
template <typename T, typename Op>
void transform(T* input, size_t count, T* output, Op op,
               const MemoryPoolContext& pool_ctx);

}  // namespace world::parallel
```

### Memory pool context

The pointer+count API enables passing memory pool metadata that iterator APIs cannot carry:

```cpp
struct MemoryPoolContext {
    int device_id;              // which world processing device
    int numa_node;              // which NUMA node the allocation is on
    MemoryPoolId pool_id;       // which pool (for accounting)
    TransportBackend backend;   // Shm, Rtps, IntraProcess

    // Backend can use this to schedule work on the optimal IPU
    // e.g., if data is on NUMA node 1, schedule on IPU group 1
};
```

### Usage in pub/sub-loop

```cpp
// Transport layer: process individual states from zero-copy region
void process_region(transport::ZeroCopyRegion& region) {
    auto* states = region.data<IndividualState>();
    size_t count = region.count();

    // Direct pointer API — no iterator wrapping
    world::parallel::transform(
        states, count, states,
        [](IndividualState& s) { s.position += s.velocity * dt; },
        region.memory_context()  // includes NUMA affinity
    );
}
```

