## Description

@pub-sub-loop-common · P3 · FEA · Claude-G

### Problem

The `autosp_jit` (automatic state processing JIT) system in the common module uses the legacy `<nv/target>` header for compile-time architecture detection. A newer version of `<nv/target>` is available that provides:

1. **Finer-grained feature queries**: not just `sm_90` but `sm_90a` (with accelerator features) vs `sm_90` (without)
2. **Forward compatibility**: `NV_IF_TARGET(NV_IS_AT_LEAST_SM_90)` correctly handles future architectures beyond sm_100
3. **Constexpr support**: target queries are `constexpr` instead of preprocessor macros, enabling use in template metaprogramming

### Current code (legacy target queries)

```cpp
// autosp_jit currently uses:
#if __CUDA_ARCH__ >= 900
    // sm_90+ code path
#elif __CUDA_ARCH__ >= 800
    // sm_80+ code path
#else
    // fallback
#endif
```

### Proposed migration

```cpp
// New: use <nv/target> constexpr queries
#include <nv/target>

NV_IF_TARGET(NV_IS_AT_LEAST_SM_90a, (
    // sm_90a: has TMA, DSMEM, warpgroup MMA
    // Used for: optimized individual state processing with hardware async copy
    use_tma_state_transfer();
), NV_IS_AT_LEAST_SM_90, (
    // sm_90 without accelerator: has clusters but not full TMA
    use_cluster_state_transfer();
), NV_IS_AT_LEAST_SM_80, (
    // sm_80: Ampere — has cp.async but not TMA
    use_cpasync_state_transfer();
), (
    // Fallback: pre-Ampere
    use_basic_state_transfer();
))
```

### Impact on autosp_jit

`autosp_jit` generates individual state processing kernels at runtime. With the new `<nv/target>`:

```cpp
// autosp_jit can select optimal kernel variants at compile time
template <typename IndividualStateT>
auto select_processing_kernel() {
    if constexpr (nv::target::is_at_least_sm_90a) {
        return tma_optimized_kernel<IndividualStateT>{};
    } else if constexpr (nv::target::is_at_least_sm_80) {
        return cpasync_kernel<IndividualStateT>{};
    } else {
        return basic_kernel<IndividualStateT>{};
    }
}
```

## Dependencies

- Requires: updated `<nv/target>` header (shipped with CUDA Toolkit 12.0+)
- Affects: `autosp_jit` and any code using `__CUDA_ARCH__` directly
- Related: world::RuntimeCompiler (common PRD #6) — JIT-compiled kernels also need target queries

