## Background

In pub/sub-loop's **WorldExtension (world_x)** layer, **Individual State Streams** (`IndividualStateStream<T>`) are lazy, composable sequences of state updates flowing through the world's pub/sub bus. They are the primary abstraction for expressing data-flow between individuals—analogous to CUDA streams for async GPU work, but applied to individual state propagation.

Two fundamental stream composition operations are missing:

- **`replicate(stream, N)`**: broadcast one upstream state stream to N downstream consumers (fan-out). Each consumer receives an independent copy of every state update.
- **`join(stream_a, stream_b, ...)`**: merge multiple upstream state streams into a single downstream stream (fan-in). The joined stream emits a tuple of states when all input streams have produced a new value (rendezvous join) or emits whichever value arrives first (racing join).

These are essential for implementing composite individual topologies: a transformer individual needs `replicate` to broadcast encoded attention state to multiple decode heads, and `join` to combine all decode head outputs into a final state.

## Problem Analysis

### Current Limitation

```cpp
// world_x/stream.h — current API
template <typename T>
class IndividualStateStream {
public:
  // Existing operations
  auto map(auto fn) -> IndividualStateStream<decltype(fn(T{}))>;
  auto filter(auto pred) -> IndividualStateStream<T>;
  auto take(size_t n) -> IndividualStateStream<T>;

  // MISSING: replicate and join
};
```

Without `replicate` and `join`:
- Fan-out to multiple individuals requires manually cloning state and publishing to multiple topics (error-prone, inconsistent)
- Fan-in from multiple individuals requires bespoke synchronization logic per composite individual
- Composite individual state merging (e.g., multi-head attention: 8 decode heads → 1 merged output) cannot be expressed declaratively

### Impact

- Composite individual (transformer) topology cannot be expressed with stream combinators
- Developers write ad-hoc pub/sub wiring for every fan-out/fan-in pattern
- No backpressure semantics for replicated streams (slow consumer blocks fast producer)

## Design

### `replicate`: Fan-Out Stream

```cpp
// world_x/stream_ops.h
namespace world_x {

// replicate: broadcast one stream to N independent consumer streams
// Each consumer gets its own buffered copy; backpressure is per-consumer
template <typename T, size_t N>
std::array<IndividualStateStream<T>, N> replicate(IndividualStateStream<T> source);

// Dynamic-N version (runtime-determined fan-out count)
template <typename T>
std::vector<IndividualStateStream<T>> replicate(IndividualStateStream<T> source, size_t n);

// Usage:
IndividualStateStream<AttentionState> attn_stream = encode_sub.output_stream();

// Replicate to 8 decode heads
auto [head0, head1, head2, head3,
      head4, head5, head6, head7] = replicate<AttentionState, 8>(attn_stream);

decode_heads_[0].set_input(head0);
decode_heads_[1].set_input(head1);
// ...
```

### `join`: Fan-In Stream (Rendezvous)

```cpp
// Rendezvous join: emits tuple only when ALL inputs have new values
template <typename... Ts>
IndividualStateStream<std::tuple<Ts...>> join(IndividualStateStream<Ts>... streams);

// Racing join: emits std::variant when ANY input produces a value
template <typename... Ts>
IndividualStateStream<std::variant<Ts...>> join_any(IndividualStateStream<Ts>... streams);

// Usage: join 8 decode head outputs into one merged state
auto merged_stream = join(
  decode_heads_[0].output_stream<DecodeState>(),
  decode_heads_[1].output_stream<DecodeState>(),
  // ...8 total
);

// merged_stream emits std::tuple<DecodeState x8> once all heads complete
merged_stream.subscribe([this](auto tuple_state) {
  auto final_state = merge_decode_heads(tuple_state);
  individual_publish(self_handle_, final_state);
});
```

### Composite Individual Topology: Multi-Head Attention

```
Encode Sub-Individual
  └── output: AttentionState stream
        │
        replicate<AttentionState, 8>
        │  │  │  │  │  │  │  │
        H0 H1 H2 H3 H4 H5 H6 H7   ← 8 Decode Head Sub-Individuals
        │  │  │  │  │  │  │  │
        └──┴──┴──┴──join──┴──┘
                      │
            tuple<DecodeState x8>
                      │
              merge_decode_heads()
                      │
            TransformerIndividual publishes FinalState
                      │
              World Pub/Sub Bus (RTPS/DDS)
```

### Backpressure Protocol

For `replicate`, each consumer has an independent ring buffer:
- If consumer N is slow (buffer full), the replicated stream applies backpressure to the **source** only for consumer N's channel
- Other consumers are unaffected
- Backpressure events emit `DiagnosticEvent{PubSubOverflow, individual_id=head_N}`

```cpp
// Backpressure configuration
struct ReplicateOptions {
  size_t buffer_per_consumer = 64;           // ring buffer depth per consumer
  BackpressurePolicy policy = BackpressurePolicy::DropOldest; // or Block, DropNewest
};

template <typename T, size_t N>
std::array<IndividualStateStream<T>, N> replicate(
  IndividualStateStream<T> source,
  ReplicateOptions opts = {}
);
```

### Stream Lifecycle and Individual Interaction

```
Stream ownership rules:
- replicate() consumes source stream (moves it)
- Returned consumer streams are independently owned by each consumer individual
- join() consumes all input streams
- The joined stream is owned by the compositor individual

Thread safety:
- Each stream's internal ring buffer is SPSC (single-producer single-consumer)
- replicate() uses N independent SPSC buffers — no cross-consumer locking
- join() uses a rendezvous latch per tick cycle — lightweight atomic synchronization
```

