## Background

This is the targeted **fix PR** for the uninitialized memory read (MSan) class of sanitizer errors in `collection::MergeSort`, tracked in the parent bug report. This PR focuses specifically on:

1. The uninitialized state field read in the merge comparator
2. The uninitialized temp buffer in the merge phase (partially-written elements)

The concurrent sort/publish race condition (ASan heap-use-after-free) is addressed in the epoch snapshot PR (separate).

## Problem: Uninitialized Memory Reads

### Comparator Read on Uninit State Field

```cpp
// collection/merge_sort.h — BEFORE FIX
bool MergeSort::compare(IndividualHandle a, IndividualHandle b) {
  // MSan ERROR: priority_score read before sub-individual has published any state
  // Newly created sub-individuals in a composite have zero-filled state structs
  // but logically their state fields are "not yet computed"
  return a.state()->priority_score < b.state()->priority_score;
}
```

**Why this matters for composite individuals**: In a transformer individual, when `encode` sub-individual is created but hasn't completed its first publish cycle, its `priority_score` field in the shared state struct is physically present (zero-initialized by allocator) but semantically uninitialized. MSan correctly flags this as a logical error because the value was never *written* by the individual—it was only implicitly zero-filled by `calloc`.

### Uninitialized Temp Buffer Elements

```cpp
// collection/merge_sort.h — BEFORE FIX
void merge(IndividualHandle* lo, IndividualHandle* mid, IndividualHandle* hi) {
  size_t n = hi - lo;
  // BUG: temp is uninitialized (malloc, not calloc)
  IndividualHandle* temp = (IndividualHandle*)malloc(n * sizeof(IndividualHandle));
  // Only left half [lo, mid) is copied into temp[0..left_size-1]
  // temp[left_size..n-1] is NEVER WRITTEN — MSan: uninit read when merge loop accesses these
  memcpy(temp, lo, left_size * sizeof(IndividualHandle));
  // ...
  // merge loop may read temp[i] where i >= left_size → uninit read
}
```

## Fix Implementation

### Fix 1: State Initialization Guard + Sentinel Ordering

```cpp
// world/individual_handle.h — ADD:
class IndividualHandle {
public:
  // Returns true if individual has completed at least one state publish cycle
  bool state_initialized() const noexcept {
    return state_epoch_.load(std::memory_order_acquire) > 0;
  }

  // Returns the state epoch counter (0 = never published)
  uint64_t state_epoch() const noexcept {
    return state_epoch_.load(std::memory_order_relaxed);
  }

private:
  std::atomic<uint64_t> state_epoch_{0};  // incremented on each successful publish
};
```

```cpp
// collection/merge_sort.h — FIXED comparator:
bool MergeSort::compare(const IndividualHandle& a, const IndividualHandle& b) const {
  const bool a_init = a.state_initialized();
  const bool b_init = b.state_initialized();

  // Sentinel ordering: uninitialized individuals always sort after initialized ones
  // This is stable and deterministic — uninitialized order is undefined but safe
  if (a_init != b_init) return a_init;   // initialized sorts before uninitialized
  if (!a_init && !b_init) return false;  // both uninit: equal (stable)

  // Both initialized: safe to read state field
  // MSan FIXED: state_initialized() guarantees at least one publish has written this field
  return a.state()->priority_score < b.state()->priority_score;
}
```

### Fix 2: Temp Buffer Initialization

```cpp
// collection/merge_sort.h — FIXED merge():
void MergeSort::merge(IndividualHandle* lo, IndividualHandle* mid, IndividualHandle* hi) {
  // FIXED: use std::vector — zero-initializes and tracks exact element count
  // Only copy [lo, mid) into temp — exactly left_size elements, no more
  std::vector<IndividualHandle> temp(lo, mid);  // copies [lo, mid), no uninit elements

  const IndividualHandle* i_end = temp.data() + temp.size();
  IndividualHandle* i = temp.data();  // pointer into left-half copy
  IndividualHandle* j = mid;          // pointer into right half (in-place)
  IndividualHandle* k = lo;           // write pointer

  while (i != i_end && j != hi) {
    // FIXED: both i and j are within their respective initialized ranges
    *k++ = compare(*i, *j) ? *i++ : *j++;
  }

  // Copy remaining left elements (i..i_end): all initialized, within temp's bounds
  while (i != i_end) {
    *k++ = *i++;
  }
  // Right remainder [j..hi) is already in place — no copy needed
}
```

### State Epoch Increment on Publish

```cpp
// world/individual_state_store.cpp
void IndividualStateStore::apply_publish(IndividualHandle& h, StateUpdate update) {
  // Write new state
  *h.state() = update.new_state;
  // Increment epoch: signals state_initialized() == true for first publish
  h.state_epoch_.fetch_add(1, std::memory_order_release);
}
```

### Composite Individual: Sub-Individual Init Ordering

For composite individuals, the parent should not sort sub-individuals until all have completed their first publish:

```cpp
// collection/individual_collection.h
void IndividualCollection::sort_by_state() {
  // Count uninitialized individuals — emit diagnostic if any
  size_t uninit_count = std::count_if(
    individuals_.begin(), individuals_.end(),
    [](const IndividualHandle& h) { return !h.state_initialized(); }
  );

  if (uninit_count > 0) {
    diag_emitter_.emit({
      .severity = Severity::Warn,
      .category = Category::StateCorruption,
      .message  = std::to_string(uninit_count) +
                  " individuals have uninitialized state; sorting to end of collection"
    });
  }

  // Sort proceeds safely: comparator handles uninit via sentinel ordering
  MergeSort sorter(individuals_);
  sorter.sort();
}
```

