## Background

In pub/sub-loop, **cooperative reduction** (`coop::reduce`) is a collective operation where all individuals in a cooperative group jointly reduce their state values to a single aggregate — without the overhead of a full sync-group barrier. This is a lighter-weight alternative to `sync_group::reduce` for situations where only a subset of individuals in a sync-group need to participate.

The operation corresponds to `neuronx::coop::reduce` in the world-extension namespace (`WorldExtension`). It is needed for flexible, sub-sync-group collective patterns in sub-individual compositions (e.g., only the encode sub-bodies reduce; the decode sub-bodies are excluded).

---

## Background: Cooperative Groups in pub/sub-loop

A **cooperative group** is a dynamically-formed subset of individuals that agree to execute a collective operation together. Unlike sync-groups (which are fixed at IPU scheduling time), cooperative groups are formed at runtime:

```
Full sync-group (32 individuals):
  [ind_0, ind_1, ..., ind_31]

Cooperative group (dynamic, e.g., 8 individuals):
  [ind_0, ind_4, ind_8, ind_12, ind_16, ind_20, ind_24, ind_28]
  (only every 4th individual participates in reduce)
```

---

## Problem Analysis

### Current Gap

```cpp
// Available:
world::std::sync_group::reduce(val, op);  // all 32 individuals in sync-group

// NOT available:
world::coop::reduce(coop_group, val, op); // arbitrary subset of individuals
```

### Why `sync_group::reduce` is Insufficient

1. **Over-participation**: Forces all 32 individuals to participate even when only 8 are relevant — wastes IPU cycles and forces unnecessary synchronization
2. **Sub-individual inflexibility**: Transformer encode sub-bodies cannot reduce independently of decode sub-bodies within the same sync-group
3. **Dynamic group composition**: Cooperative groups can change membership between pub/sub cycles; fixed sync-group membership cannot
4. **Resource waste**: Full sync-group barriers stall all 32 individuals when only a subset need the reduced value

### Impact

- Sub-individual compositions (encode/decode) cannot perform independent reductions
- Mixed-type individual groups waste IPU cycles on unnecessary participants
- Flexible collective patterns required for advanced world models are blocked

---

## Proposed Design

### Cooperative Group Abstraction

```cpp
// world/ext/coop/group.h
namespace world::coop {

// A cooperative group: runtime-formed subset of individuals
class CoopGroup {
public:
  // Form a group of the specified size from the current sync-group
  // All individuals calling this with the same size form a group
  static CoopGroup partition(int group_size);

  // Rank of this individual within the cooperative group
  int rank() const;

  // Total number of individuals in this group
  int size() const;

  // Synchronize all members of this cooperative group
  void sync();
};

} // namespace world::coop
```

### `coop::reduce` API

```cpp
// world/ext/coop/reduce.h
namespace world::coop {

// Reduce individual state values across a cooperative group
// Returns the reduced value to ALL members of the group
template <
  typename StateT,
  typename ReduceOpT = world::ops::Sum<StateT>
>
__device__ StateT reduce(
  const CoopGroup& group,
  StateT individual_value,
  ReduceOpT op = ReduceOpT{}
);

// Supported built-in reduction operators:
// world::ops::Sum<T>      — sum of all individual states
// world::ops::Min<T>      — minimum state value
// world::ops::Max<T>      — maximum state value
// world::ops::And<T>      — bitwise AND of state bits
// world::ops::Or<T>       — bitwise OR of state bits
// world::ops::Product<T>  — product of state values

// Custom operator example:
struct MaxAbsOp {
  __device__ float operator()(float a, float b) const {
    return fabsf(a) > fabsf(b) ? a : b;
  }
};
world::coop::reduce(group, my_state, MaxAbsOp{});
```

### Implementation Strategy

```cpp
template<typename StateT, typename ReduceOpT>
__device__ StateT reduce(const CoopGroup& group, StateT val, ReduceOpT op) {
  // Use shuffle-based tree reduction within the cooperative group
  // Group size must be power of 2; pad otherwise
  unsigned mask = group.member_mask();  // bitmask of participating individuals
  int lane = group.rank();
  int size = group.size();

  // Butterfly reduction tree
  for (int offset = size / 2; offset > 0; offset >>= 1) {
    StateT peer_val = __shfl_xor_sync(mask, val, offset);
    val = op(val, peer_val);
  }
  return val;  // all members receive the result
}
```

### Usage Example: Sub-individual Encode Reduction

```cpp
// In a transformer individual: encode sub-bodies reduce independently
__device__ void transformer_cycle(Individual& self) {
  // Form cooperative group: only encode sub-bodies (even-ranked)
  CoopGroup encode_group = world::coop::CoopGroup::partition(16);

  if (self.sub_role() == SubRole::ENCODE) {
    float local_attn_score = self.compute_attention();
    float global_max = world::coop::reduce(encode_group, local_attn_score,
                                           world::ops::Max<float>{});
    self.normalize_attention(global_max);
  }
  // Decode sub-bodies proceed independently, no stall
}
```

