## Description

In the current pub/sub-loop architecture, individual state transitions that require stochastic sampling (e.g., exploration policies in autonomous agent individuals, probabilistic belief state updates, Monte Carlo sub-body simulations) rely on ad-hoc random number generation scattered across modules. There is no unified, hardware-accelerated random number generation facility available to individuals during their pub/sub cycles.

The legacy approach mirrors what CUDA developers faced before cuRand: each kernel (now: each individual state processor / IPU) would implement its own LCG or xorshift generator with no guarantee of statistical quality, no support for different distributions, and poor performance under concurrent world-state updates. In the pub/sub-loop context, when hundreds of individual state processing units (IPUs) simultaneously execute state-update kernels, these ad-hoc generators produce correlated sequences that corrupt Monte Carlo estimates and break stochastic sub-body interactions.

The `IndividualStateSync` module (mapped from TensorParallel) coordinates multi-IPU simultaneous processing of a single individual's state dimensions. When that individual's state update requires random sampling—for example, a reinforcement-learning agent individual sampling an action from a policy distribution, or a particle-filter individual resampling its belief particles—each IPU must draw from an independent, high-quality random stream. Without a cuRand-equivalent facility, this is impossible to guarantee.

**Affected modules:**
- `cyber/collection/individual_state_sync` — primary consumer
- `modules/scheduler` — stochastic scheduling policies need RNG
- `modules/transport` — probabilistic packet-drop simulation for fault-injection testing
- `modules/data` — synthetic data generation for individual initialization
- `modules/component` — component-level Monte Carlo state estimation

**Current broken pattern:**
```cpp
// CURRENT: each IPU uses ad-hoc LCG — correlated, low quality
struct IPUStateKernel {
    uint64_t seed;

    __device__ float next_random() {
        // LCG with poor constants — correlation across IPUs!
        seed = seed * 6364136223846793005ULL + 1442695040888963407ULL;
        return (seed >> 33) * (1.0f / (1ULL << 31));
    }

    __device__ void update_individual_state(IndividualState& state) {
        // Stochastic state update with correlated RNG — WRONG
        float r = next_random();
        state.belief_weight *= (r > 0.5f) ? 1.1f : 0.9f;
    }
};
```

**Proposed fix — unified WorldRNG facility:**
```cpp
// NEW: WorldRNG mirrors cuRand API adapted for pub/sub-loop
#include <world/rng/world_rng.hpp>

namespace world::rng {

// Generator types (mirrors curandRngType_t)
enum class WorldRngType {
    PHILOX_4X32_10,    // Best for parallel IPU use
    XORWOW,           // Legacy compatibility
    MRG32K3A,         // Long period, high quality
    QUASI_SOBOL,      // Low-discrepancy for integration
};

// Per-IPU RNG state — fits in ISG shared memory
struct alignas(16) IPURngState {
    uint4 philox_state;
    uint32_t subsequence_id;  // unique per IPU in ISG
    uint32_t offset;
};

// World-level RNG manager
class WorldRngManager {
public:
    // Initialize with world seed — reproducible across runs
    void initialize(uint64_t world_seed, WorldRngType type = WorldRngType::PHILOX_4X32_10);

    // Assign independent subsequences to each IPU
    void assign_ipu_states(IPURngState* d_states, size_t num_ipus);

    // Generate samples for individual state update
    template<typename Distribution>
    void generate_for_individual(
        IndividualId id,
        IPURngState& ipu_state,
        float* output,
        size_t count,
        Distribution dist
    );
};

// Distribution adapters
struct UniformDistribution { float low, high; };
struct NormalDistribution   { float mean, stddev; };
struct PoissonDistribution  { float lambda; };
struct ExponentialDistribution { float lambda; };

} // namespace world::rng

// Usage in IndividualStateSync kernel:
__global__ void sync_individual_states_stochastic(
    IndividualState* states,
    IPURngState* rng_states,
    size_t num_individuals
) {
    size_t ipu_id = blockIdx.x * blockDim.x + threadIdx.x;
    if (ipu_id >= num_individuals) return;

    IPURngState& rng = rng_states[ipu_id];
    IndividualState& state = states[ipu_id];

    // High-quality, independent random sample per IPU
    float sample = world::rng::sample_uniform(rng, 0.0f, 1.0f);
    state.belief_weight *= (sample > 0.5f) ? 1.1f : 0.9f;

    // Normal distribution for Gaussian noise injection
    float noise = world::rng::sample_normal(rng, 0.0f, state.noise_stddev);
    state.position += noise;
}
